In", "id_str": "2063378160474095892", "in_reply_to_screen_name": "CharlesMullins2", "in_reply_to_status_id_str": "2063355772554150164", "in_reply_to_user_id_str": "747142327", "is_quote_status": false, "lang": "en", "quote_count": 0, "reply_count": 0, "retweet_count": 2, "retweeted": false, "user_id_str": "1510953191948570632"}, "note_tweet": {"is_expandable": true, "note_tweet_results": {"result": {"entity_set": {"hashtags": [], "symbols": [], "urls": [], "user_mentions": []}, "id": "Tm90ZVR3ZWV0OjIwNjMzNzgxNjAzNzM0MzIzMjA=", "text": "This is the kind of breakthrough that could completely transform:
sensing;
photonics;
and AI–environment interfaces.
The truly revolutionary aspect is not just: “a spectrometer on a chip,”
but the fact that: the material structure itself becomes: an optical processor.
In practice: plastic is no longer just a passive substrate.
It becomes: geometrically programmed matter for light processing.
What is especially interesting is that: the laser-induced micro-vortices create: local phase and interference structures.

Within NMSI, this is highly relevant, because it strongly resembles:
phase routing;
resonant nodes;
and distributed coherent processing.
Such structures could become extremely valuable for: GPU Coherent:
integrated optical sensors;
local spectral feedback;
phase monitoring;
and ultra-compact coherent readout.
In practice: matter is beginning: not just to transport light, but: to structurally “interpret” it."}}}, "rest_id": "2063378160474095892", "source": "<a href="http://twitter.com/download/android" rel="nofollow">Twitter for Android</a>", "unmention_data": {}, "views": {"count": "277", "state": "EnabledWithCount"}}

